Title: Documentary photograph of children holding MWRO flag at public welfare office demonstration
Abstract: This black and white photograph from August 27, 1971, depicts a demonstration organized by the Mothers' Welfare Rights Organization (MWRO) in front of a Public Welfare office on Howkins Street. The image centers on an 8-year-old girl holding a large MWRO flag, flanked by another young girl and a partially obscured child. The photograph captures a moment of social activism, highlighting the participation of children in advocating for welfare rights.

Abstract: This aerial photograph captures Logan International Airport in Boston, highlighting the ongoing construction and expansion of the airport. The image showcases the newly built Northeast Hangar and the former Terminal B5, providing a visual representation of the airport's growth and modernization. The composition emphasizes the scale of the project, with vast stretches of land undergoing development, signifying the airport's increasing capacity and importance.

Title: Documentary photograph of crowd gathering at Boston Common demonstration
Abstract: This black and white photograph, taken on May 9, 1968, by Boston Globe staff photographer Fletcher, captures a demonstration on Boston Common. The image shows a large crowd of people, with a group of African American men in suits walking in the center. The photograph, titled "Alternative arrives," suggests the arrival of a new movement or perspective, likely related to the "Pow Perjio March" mentioned in the accompanying information.

Title: Documentary photograph of portable machine shops at East Boston Airport
Abstract: This photograph, taken on August 11, 1950, shows portable machine shops at the East Boston Air Port. The composition is centered on a large, rectangular building on wheels, likely serving as the portable shop. The building features multiple windows and a door with steps, suggesting a functional workspace. The presence of an airplane hangar in the background further emphasizes the image's airport setting.

Title: Documentary photograph of Northeast Airlines Skymaster landing at Logan Airport
Abstract: This black and white photograph, taken before 1950, depicts a Northeast Airlines Skymaster airplane landing on a newly completed runway at Logan International Airport. The photograph captures the moment the plane touches down on the 6,000-foot runway after a 55-minute flight from New York. The image highlights the significance of the new runway for the airport and the role of Northeast Airlines in its inauguration.

Title: Documentary photograph of anti-war protestors in Washington, D.C.
Abstract: This black and white photograph, taken on March 25, 1967, depicts a group of anti-war demonstrators marching on a city street. The photograph focuses on a young Black man in the foreground carrying a sign reading "RETURN GOOD FOR EVIL." Other protesters can be seen behind him, some holding signs with peace symbols. The presence of snow on the ground suggests a cold day. The image captures the spirit of protest and dissent against the Vietnam War in the late 1960s.

Title: Illustration Commemorating the First Official Landing in the United States of the U.S. Army Round-the-World Flight
Abstract: This stone plaque commemorates the first official landing in the United States of the U.S. Army's first around-the-world flight, which took place at Boston Airport on September 6, 1924. The plaque depicts an eagle carrying an airplane over a globe, symbolizing the global reach of aviation. It also lists the names and planes of the pilots who participated in the historic flight.

Title: Illustration of Logan Airport and Hotel Loganaire in East Boston
Abstract: This simple line drawing map from January 21, 1958, depicts the planned location of the Hotel Loganaire in East Boston. The map highlights the hotel's proximity to Logan International Airport, the Jeffries Point Yacht Club, and the Boston Navy Yard. The map also shows major roads and the South Apron Area of the airport.
